# Reading in Data
big_sky_revenue <- read.csv(file = "/Users/zacharyhiga/Documents/Big_Sky_Revenue_2018.csv", header = T)

# Setting the variables of Sport and School as factors
big_sky_revenue$Sport <- as.factor(big_sky_revenue$Sport)
big_sky_revenue$School <- as.factor(big_sky_revenue$School)

# RCB Experimental Design
big_sky_revenue.lm <- lm(Revenue ~ Sport + School, data = big_sky_revenue)

# Taking the ANOVA of the fitted RCB model
anova(big_sky_revenue.lm)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Revenue
##           Df     Sum Sq    Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Sport      5 2.0608e+14 4.1216e+13 74.9742 <2e-16 ***
## School     9 7.8993e+12 8.7771e+11  1.5966 0.1453    
## Residuals 45 2.4738e+13 5.4973e+11                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Plotting the model
plot(big_sky_revenue.lm)

# Using box-cox to take a look at the assumptions
library(MASS)
## Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 4.0.5
boxcox(Revenue ~ Sport + School, data = big_sky_revenue, lambda = seq(-2.00, 2.00, length = 50))

# Performing a log-transformation on the data and fitting a model with this transformation
big_sky_revenue$logRevenue <- log10(big_sky_revenue$Revenue)
big_sky_revenue_log.lm <- lm(logRevenue ~ Sport + School, data = big_sky_revenue)

# Taking the ANOVA of the model after the transformation
anova(big_sky_revenue_log.lm)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: logRevenue
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value    Pr(>F)    
## Sport      5 9.8436 1.96873 170.4731 < 2.2e-16 ***
## School     9 0.3034 0.03371   2.9187  0.008243 ** 
## Residuals 45 0.5197 0.01155                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Plotting the transformed model
plot(big_sky_revenue_log.lm)
